body:
1. In this class my goal was to become more familiar with the software used in digital design

2. As the class progressed I became increasingly interested in the principles of design that make art aesthetically pleasing.

3. The progression of the class is very organic and beginner-friendly. Starting with Illustrator made learning Photoshop less tedious and sprinkling in design principles helped maximize learning while getting a good mix of everything. It was also very easy to learn/do the assignments remotely which was nice!

4. the problems that plagued me were not because of the course material or instruction. I am the worst procrastinator on this planet I left a lot to do in the last couple of weeks. 

5. GET YOUR ASSIGNMENTS DONE ON TIME! Put in a little every day.

6. The biggest lesson I think I learned was the importance of revisions and feedback. For many of the projects, we had to post a work in progress to get some external thoughts. This helped maximize the potential of our designs and taught me that feedback is one of the best resources we have. A design could be shown to anyone in the world and as a result of this anyone can provide valuable information on the first impressions of a piece. Another lesson I learned is that genius is in the simple details. A design's greatness is a sum of small, barely noticeable details. For example, we learned a lot about fonts and typography. Typography is something you don't consciously think about because you're just reading the word. But little details like the kerning and spacing can help convey ideas and emotions, reinforcing the meaning of your design.

body:
This is the Steel Drum. The fundamental frequency is around 250 Hz, and the modes are inharmonic, and they don't all fall in the harmonic frequency patterns. They are around 550 hz, 800 Hz, 1075 Hz.

 

This is the spectrum for the Tympani. The fundamental frequency is roughly 94 Hz. and the modes are inharmonic, and they don't all fall in the harmonic frequency patterns. They are around 140 Hz, 180Hz, and 204 Hz.

Brass 

 

Liquid Nitrogen- temperature

Helium- pitch

Different mouthpieces- different pitches

Spectrogram

High Speed camera- Lip Movements depending on temp

 

Materials needed:

Spectrogram

High Speed camera

Liquid nitrogen??

Projector

 

Scholarly Sources 

University of Puget- Temperature affect on brass  https://soundideas.pugetsound.edu/faculty_pubs/1220/#:~:text=Because%20the%20speed%20of%20sound,when%20the%20air%20is%20cold. 

 

Ebsco Peer Reviewed source- Mouthpiece affect on acoustic properties:

https://research.ebsco.com/c/y34kcw/details/2rrg4rxgpz?limiters=FT1%3AY&q=physics%20of%20brass%20instruments

1. Introduction:In the introduction we will discuss how temperature can affect the pitch of the instrument and use it to justify the process of warming up and tuning instruments for a performance. 
  1. Evidence of Research: University of Puget- Temperature effect on brass . This article talks about the effect that air temperature has on brass, talking about airspeed and air resistance with differently heated enviorments.
  1. Science: The science of this is clear because it is relating to heat, airspeed, and air resistance. Assuming constant pressure, there is less and less air resistance at higher temperatures because it becomes less dense. In addition to this, metals expand when they are warm, and contract when they are cold. Because of both of these, the pitch decreases as the temperature (of both the air and instrument body) decreases
  1. Format: Our presentation will be done primarily through the use of a powerpoint. Each member of our group will have the opportunity to present an equal number of slides, ensuring that everyone contributes equally. We will also have a live demonstration of a Brass instrument showing the effect that temperature has on pitch.
  1. Timing: 10 minutes should be the perfect amount of time with the flow being dictated by the PowerPoint well be able to adapt to various circumstances and with the real time consuming element being the demonstration we can defer to that for the base the timing of the rest of the presentation. 

 

  1. Use of Demonstrations:

We will demonstrate the difference in air speed and therefore pitch of the instrument. We will do so by cooling down a brass instrument and playing it before/after a warmed up instrument so show the difference. To make the difference more clear, we'd like to use a spectrogram to show how the fundamental frequency changes. 

We will cool down the instrument and the air around it using either ice water, dry ice, or liquid nitrogen.

Discuss the purpose of lengthening/shortening the instrument in order to compensate for the air temperature changes. We will use a trombone for this.

For the next demonstration we will need a Computer (with spectrogram), a brass instrument (from ricky), and a bucket of ice (provided by Dr. Anderson)
